What run() REALLY IS

run() is not a business function.
run() is a law-enforcement engine.

It answers only one question:

“Given all declared strategic constraints — may this state change occur?”

How Each Strategic Level Manifests (Precisely)

1️⃣ System Health — Existence Gate

Strategic:
Is the system globally capable of operations?

Where it lives:

  • Engine bootstrap

  • Adapter registry readiness

  • Storage availability

How run() sees it:

  • If system is unhealthy → run() must not mutate state

  • This is usually cached, not recomputed

✅ Not an operation
✅ A prerequisite invariant

2️⃣ User Authorization — Actor Capability

Strategic:
What can this user ever do in this system?

Where it lives:

  • Role → capability matrix

  • User context attached to run_doc

How run() uses it:

  • Filters the operation universe

  • If user lacks capability → operation is invalid by definition

❌ No authorize_user() run
✅ run() refuses illegal intent

3️⃣ Operation Feasibility — Operation Ontology

Strategic:
Does this operation exist for this doctype/context?

Where it lives:

  • Adapter metadata

  • FSM operation maps

  • Config, not code

Example:

js
Task.operations = ['create', 'update', 'complete']

How run() uses it:

  • If operation is not declared → invalid reality

⚠️ This is NOT business logic
⚠️ This is the shape of the universe

4️⃣ Document Validation — Structural Truth

Strategic:
Is this document structurally real?

Examples:

  • Required fields

  • Types

  • Formats

Where it lives:

  • Schema metadata

  • Field definitions

How run() uses it:

  • Structural validation is mandatory before meaning

  • No business logic runs on invalid structure

📌 This is still pre-meaning

5️⃣ Business Logic — Domain Truth ⭐ (FSM LIVES HERE)

Strategic:
Does this transition make sense in the business domain?

This includes:

  • FSM transitions

  • Workflow rules

  • Cross-document constraints

  • Credit checks

  • Status rules

Example FSM rule:

js
state: "Submitted" → "Cancelled"
allowed: false

Where it lives:

  • Adapter domain rules

  • FSM definitions

  • Declarative policies

How run() uses it:

  • run() asks: “Is this state transition legal?”

  • If not → run fails, no mutation

✅ FSM is pure Business Logic
❌ Not Operation Feasibility
❌ Not Validation

6️⃣ Field Authorization — Visibility & Mutability

Strategic:
Which fields may this actor read/write?

Where it lives:

  • Field metadata

  • Role-based rules

How run() uses it:

  • Strips forbidden fields from input/output

  • Prevents mutation of protected fields

📌 Happens after business logic decides “yes”

7️⃣ Field Processing — Semantic Transformation

Strategic:
How does data become meaningful?

Examples:

  • Type casting

  • Derived fields

  • Computed values

  • Normalization

Where it lives:

  • Field processors

  • Adapter helpers

How run() uses it:

  • Applies transformations during mutation

  • Produces canonical state

Final Mental Model (This Is the Key Insight)

The 7 levels do not call each other.
They constrain run() from different dimensions.

run() does NOT:

  • Decide permissions

  • Invent operations

  • Define business meaning

run() DOES:

  • Enforce declared reality

  • Execute allowed transitions

  • Record causality

One-Sentence Truth

Your FSM transition logic is Business Logic (Level 5),
but it is enforced by run() operating under all 7 strategic constraints.

      • Only adapter-approved transitions

      • Failed runs do not advance state

  4. Partial authorization

    • Certain users may have restricted capabilities → partial permission runs

    • Modeled via fail-early constants (e.g., FAIL_EARLY.OPERATION_X)

  5. Dependency on Global FSM

    • User authorization transitions may depend on the system state

    • Example: user cannot reach active if global FSM is degraded

2️⃣ Run Lifecycle for User Authorization

Example: unauthenticated → authenticated

text
run() called → run_doc generated
│
├─ Adapter function: authorize_user(run_doc)
│
├─ Check `t.when` conditions:
│   - e.g., system_state === 'ready'
│   - user credentials valid
│
├─ If conditions pass → run_doc.output.final_state = 'authenticated'
│
└─ Set run_doc.success
    ├─ true → FSM approved
    └─ false → user remains in prior state

3️⃣ Projection Logic — Current User State

  • Filter runs: operation === 'authorize_user'

  • Filter by adapter-approved transitions (t.when true)

  • Latest successful run → authoritative state

  • Failed runs → stored for audit/logging

  • Fail-early constants → limit operations for this user

Pseudo-code:

js
function getCurrentUserState(userId) {
  const userRuns = CoworkerState.runs
    .filter(run => run.operation === 'authorize_user')
    .filter(run => run.input.user_id === userId)
    .filter(run => run.success && run.output?.final_state);

  if (!userRuns.length) return 'unauthenticated';

  return userRuns[userRuns.length - 1].output.final_state;
}

4️⃣ Fail-Early Constants for Users

  • Adapter can emit user-level fail-early constants:

js
run_doc.fail_early = [FAIL_EARLY.OPERATION_X, FAIL_EARLY.FIELD_Y];

  • These constants act as partial permission blocks

  • Can be checked by any future run() to prevent unauthorized actions

5️⃣ Dependency on Global FSM

  • User FSM transitions may require a system state:

js
t.when = {
  system_state: 'ready',
  credentials_valid: true
}

  • If system FSM is degraded → user may remain in unauthenticated or limited mode

  • Consistent with Level 1 projection

6️⃣ Concurrency & Retry Rules

  • Each user FSM chain is single-threaded per user

  • Multiple users may advance independently

  • Failed authorization attempts:

    • Keep previous state

    • Emit fail-early constants

    • Can be retried later

  • Unified shape

    • run_doc same as Level 1

    • success, output, error, fail_early

  • Global FSM + User FSM

    • Level 1 constrains Level 2 (user cannot exceed system capabilities)

    • Level 2 constrains business logic (users cannot perform unauthorized operations)

🔹 Level 3 — Operation Feasibility Blueprint

1️⃣ Core Principles

  1. Unified run/run_doc

    • Each feasibility check is a run()

    • Output stored in run_doc.success, run_doc.output, run_doc.error

  2. Operation FSM / Adapter

    • Each operation may define its preconditions via an adapter (similar to t.when)

    • Example:

      js
      t.when = {
  system_state: 'ready',
  user_state: 'active',
  dependencies_completed: ['Schema.load', 'Adapters.load']
}

    • Operation runs only advance if all conditions are met

  3. Fail-Early Constants

    • Partially blocked operations emit fail-early constants:

      js
      run_doc.fail_early = [FAIL_EARLY.OPERATION_X]

    • Future runs consult these constants to enforce feasibility

  4. Projection

    • “Can this operation be executed?” = derived from:

      • Global FSM state (Level 1)

      • User FSM state (Level 2)

      • Other operation dependencies (optional)

    • Only adapter-approved runs contribute to feasibility

2️⃣ Run Lifecycle — Operation Feasibility

Example: Check feasibility for create:Task

text
run() called → run_doc generated
│
├─ Adapter function: check_operation_feasibility(run_doc)
│
├─ Evaluate `t.when` conditions:
│   - system_state = ready
│   - user_state = active
│   - previous operations completed
│
├─ If conditions pass:
│   run_doc.success = true
│   run_doc.output.feasible = true
│
└─ If conditions fail:
    run_doc.success = false
    run_doc.output.feasible = false
    run_doc.fail_early = [FAIL_EARLY.OPERATION_X]

3️⃣ Projection Logic — Operation Feasibility

Pseudo-code:

js
function isOperationFeasible(userId, operationName) {
  const systemState = getCurrentState(); // Level 1
  const userState = getCurrentUserState(userId); // Level 2

  const feasibilityRuns = CoworkerState.runs
    .filter(run => run.operation === 'check_operation_feasibility')
    .filter(run => run.input.operation_name === operationName)
    .filter(run => run.input.user_id === userId);

  // Last adapter-approved feasibility run is authoritative
  const lastRun = feasibilityRuns.reverse().find(run => run.success);

  if (!lastRun) return false;

  return lastRun.output.feasible;
}

4️⃣ Dependencies & Fail-Early Integration

  • Feasibility checks may depend on:

    • System FSM (Level 1)

    • User FSM (Level 2)

    • Previous operations (flow control)

  • If any dependency fails → feasibility = false, emit fail-early

  • This creates a fail-fast chain:

    • In Level 3, blocked operations cannot run

    • Business logic (Level 5) respects fail-early constants

5️⃣ Concurrency & Retry Rules

  • Multiple feasibility runs may execute in parallel for different users or operations

  • Single operation per user must be serialized to avoid race conditions

  • Retry is allowed if dependencies change or fail-early constants are cleared

6️⃣ Summary — Level 3

ConceptRepresentation
FeasibilityDerived from adapter-approved checks + projections
DependenciesSystem state (L1), user state (L2), prior operations
FailuresEmit fail-early constants, do not block other operations unnecessarily
ProjectionLast successful feasibility run = authoritative
ConcurrencyParallel allowed across users, serialized per operation/user
Unified shapeSame run_doc structure as L1 & L2

✅ Strategic Takeaway

  • Pattern continues: Runs → Adapter FSM → projection → fail-early

  • Level 3 sits on Levels 1 & 2, adding operation dependencies

  • All future operations (business logic, document validation, field access) will consult Level 3 feasibility before executing

We can proceed to Level 4 — Document Validation, which will layer on Levels 1–3 and enforce schema correctness in the same run_doc + FSM + fail-early pattern.
